@node Install "Installation"

                            @{b}Hard Drive Installation@{ub}

Installation of Riktor could not be easier, simply drag the Riktor draw icon
into the required draw on your hard drive. The configuration file for Riktor
must be located in this draw. An example  configuration  file  Riktor.config
has  been supplied, it is therefore recommended you simply edit this file to
reflect your own lottery numbers and output requirements.

See: @{"Configuration" Link Config} for further details.

Riktor requires Workbench revision 2.04 or higher to run.

@endnode



@node Config "Configuration"

                                 @{b}Configuration@{ub}

In order for Riktor to be of any use it is necessary to provide  it  with  a
list  of  your lottery numbers. These numbers are listed in the Tickets file
using the syntax set out below.  An  example  configuration  file  has  been
included  for  convenience, the easiest way to create your own configuration
is to simply modify the existing one.

However, before this file can be used it is necessary to tell  Riktor  where
the  results of the lottery check should be sent. This is quite simple to do
by specifying the output device by setting the  Tooltypes  on  the  programs
icon.


@{b}ToolTypes@{ub}
---------


    @{b}FONT=<fontname.font>@{ub}

This tooltype is entirely optional and simply allows you to set the font  as
used by Riktor - as if you had not guessed.


    @{b}SCREEN=<public screen>@{ub}

example...

    SCREEN=Voyager - Opens Riktor on the screen of the @{"web" Link Web} browser Voyager.

Please Note: If the screen specified in the Tooltypes is unavailable, Riktor
will open on the front most screen.


    @{b}OUTPUT=<0, 1 or 2>@{ub}

Where...

    0 = CON: - (cli type) window. See the CON tooltype below.

    1 = File - Save Riktor results to a file. See FILE below.

    2 = PRT: - Send the results to the printer via the printer.device


    @{b}FILE=<filename>@{ub}

example...

    FILE="RAM:Riktor.Results"

When saving to a file as with 'RAM:Riktor.Results' above, any disk drive may
be used. Similarly, any filename can also be used - 'DH2:Lottery' would work
just as well.


    @{b}CON=<parameters>@{ub}

example...

    CON="CON:0/0/400/200/Riktor Output/CLOSE"

Please note: CON: windows will open on the workbench screen not  the  screen
as specified in the SCREEN tooltype.


    @{b}WINDOWX=<position from left>@{ub}

Position of Riktor's window from the left edge of the screen.


    @{b}WINDOWY=<position from top>@{ub}

Position of Riktor's window from the top edge of the screen.


Please Note: When you quit Riktor the  tooltypes  are  automatically  saved.
Settings  such as the window position and 'Results' cycle gadget will be set
to their current values.




@{b}Tickets File@{ub}
------------


    @

Individual lottery tickets can be named by using the @ character  to  create
ticket @labels@. If the 'label' is not @enclosed at each end@, the file will
be regarded as being invalid. Using double  @@  characters  results  in  the
following  lottery  numbers  to  be  grouped together by numbering them as a
ticket...

    @Syndicate@ - Valid for a lottery ticket label.

    @@ - This would label the proceeding lottery numbers as 'Ticket 1:' etc.

Please note - that for every opening @ character a closing @ character  MUST
be specified...

    @Syndicate - Would cause the Tickets file to be regarded as invalid.

For obvious reasons you should not try an use the @ or # characters in  your
labels!


    #

Tells Riktor the following data is a new line  of  lottery  numbers.  The  #
command should be issued in the following format...

    #01/02/03/04/05/06/

...Each number must be expressed in two digits, eg. 7 would be 07. A  single
character must be placed after each number, this could be anything you like,
but / or , are recommended for clarity. You could even use  another  number,
but that would be rather silly. :-)


That's it - the configuration file is as simple as that. Just to  make  sure
you  fully  understand  how  it should be I've inserted the supplied example
'Tickets' file below...


---Example Tickets file---

 @Syndicate@

 #01/02/03/04/05/06/
 #01/37/32/35/41/42/
 #18/19/21/24/33/44/
 #03/07/29/30/32/43/
 #20/23/27/32/33/49/

 @@

 #07/08/12/18/34/35/
 #02/09/13/25/26/47/

---End---


@endnode



@node Usage "Usage"

                             @{b}How to Use Riktor@{ub}

Once you have edited the @{"Tickets" Link Config} file, using Riktor could not be easier...

When initially run, the  first  ball-number  gadget  will  be  automatically
activated.  Simply  enter  each ball number in turn, pressing the return key
after each entry. Only numbers between 1-49 may  be  entered  and  duplicate
entries  are also checked for. If either of these conditions is not meet you
will be given a suitable error message and the gadget  will  be  reactivated
for you to try again.

Once all seven numbers have been entered, Riktor will attempt  to  read  the
configuration  file  and  if  all  goes  well the results will be displayed,
printed or saved to a file depending on your tooltype settings.


    @{b}Restart@{ub}

You may, if you wish use this button to clear all the entries  and  re-enter
the  numbers  from scratch. Again once you've entered the last number (bonus
ball) the results will be returned immediately. The keyboard short-cut for
this function is R.


    @{b}Check@{ub}

Once you have obtained your first set of results from when Riktor  was  run,
you  may  edit  any  of the numbers and perform another check. Once you have
made any necessary alterations just hit the Check button to get the new  set
of results. The keyboard short-cut for 'Check' is C.


    @{b}Results@{ub}

This cycle gadget allows you to select the method of output for the  lottery
number  check.  You can choose from CON: File or Print. You may also set the
parameters for the CON: option and the path/filename for  the  File  option.
For further details please see @{"Configuration" Link config}

@endnode



